    "biasType": "Opinion Statements Presented as Fact",
    "biasedText": "To rob me of that opportunity is a sin.",
    "explanation": "The author uses unequivocal moral language to describe lack of congressional war debate as a 'sin,' presenting a subjective judgment as if it were a fact."
  },
  {
    "biasType": "Sensationalism/Emotionalism",
    "biasedText": "we’re sitting around waiting to see if he has decided whether he’ll launch a war with Iran. There are 435 members of the House of Representatives, there are 100 members of the Senate, and yet the most sacred decision that a nation’s political leadership can take will come down to one man’s mood. ... Better hope the president sleeps well tonight.",
    "explanation": "The author uses dramatic and emotional rhetoric ('one man's mood,' 'Better hope the president sleeps well tonight') to sensationalize the president's power and create anxiety around the decision-making process."
  },
  {
    "biasType": "Spin",
    "biasedText": "Congress’s abdication of its role made our system of government more functional, our politics more harmonious, and our ability to assign blame easier? Or has it been a slow-motion disaster that ought to be rethought from the ground up...",
    "explanation": "The language frames Congress’s historical lack of involvement in war decisions as potentially disastrous without acknowledging arguments in favor of executive control, presenting the situation negatively to persuade readers."
  },
  {
    "biasType": "Subjective Qualifying Adjectives",
    "biasedText": "timorously acquiesce until it could no longer stomach its own impotence",
    "explanation": "Describing Congress as 'timorously' acquiescing and unable to 'stomach its own impotence' employs pejorative and subjective adjectives to characterize congressional actions, conveying the author's negative view as fact."
  }
]

